Found it. There are two mismatched indexing schemes that cancel out on a square image but break on non-square ones.

The core problem: two different linearization strategies are used.

1. Image loading loop (blur.cu:80-85) — column-major order:


for(int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
    for(int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
        // stores pixel at index: x * height + y  (column-major)
This iterates x (column) in the outer loop, y (row) in the inner loop, so pixel (x, y) lands at index x * height + y.

2. The kernel (blur.cu:41-43) — row-major order:


in[curRow * width + curCol]
The kernel expects pixel (col, row) at index row * width + col (row-major).

3. The output loop (blur.cu:117-122) — also column-major:


int pos = x * height + y;
This reads back using column-major, which matches the load loop but not the kernel.

When width == height (e.g. 800×800), row * width + col and col * height + row produce the same values, so the bug is invisible. On any non-square image, the kernel reads/writes pixels from the wrong positions.

The fix: Make everything consistent. The simplest approach is to make the load and save loops row-major to match the kernel — swap the loop order so y (row) is outer and x (col) is inner, and update the index to y * width + x:


// Loading:
for(int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
    for(int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
        bmp.get_pixel(x, y, color);
        input_image.push_back({color.red, color.green, color.blue});
    }
}

// Saving:
for(int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
    for(int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
        int pos = y * width + x;
        bmp.set_pixel(x, y, output_image[pos].x, output_image[pos].y, output_image[pos].z);
    }
}
This makes the host-side layout match what the kernel expects: pixel (x, y) at index y * width + x.

